his preeminent group of scholars probes the continuity and diversity of modes of personhood across a range of Western and non-Western societies. Contributors consider what happens to individual subjectivity when stable or imagined environments such as nations and communities are transformed or displaced by free trade economics, terrorism, and war; how new information and medical technologies reshape the relation one has to oneself; and which forms of subjectivity and life possibilities are produced against a world in pieces. The transdisciplinary conversation includes anthropologists, historians of science, psychologists, a literary critic, a philosopher, physicians, and an economist. The authors touch on how we think and write about contingency, human agency, and ethics today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEthnologyxPhilosophy. 0aEthnologyxResearch. 0aEthnopsychology. 0aMedical anthropology. 0aSubjectivity. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aanthropologists.  aeconomists.  aethnographers.  aethnography.  afree trade economics.  ahuman agency.  aliterary critics.  amedical technologies.  amodern philosophy.  amodern subject.  amodes of being.  amultidisciplinary.  anational identity.  anationalism.  anonfiction.  anonwestern societies.  apersonal identity.  apersonal lives.  apersonhood.  aphilosophers.  aphysicians.  apsychologists.  ascience historians.  asocial scholars.  asocial sciences.  asubjectivity.  aterrorism.  atransformed communities.  awar.  awestern societies.1 aBiehl, João, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiehl, João, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aCorin, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDas, Ranendra K.